and humanity lose?

01:10:49.930 --> 01:10:52.040
And unfortunately,
that's the conclusion.

01:10:52.040 --> 01:10:56.490
And in this study, in the
movie, there are no heroes,

01:10:56.490 --> 01:11:01.160
except the woman who challenges
me, confronts me to say,

01:11:01.160 --> 01:11:03.557
what you're doing is wrong,
that these are not prisoners,

01:11:03.557 --> 01:11:05.890
they're not guards, they're
boys, and they're suffering,

01:11:05.890 --> 01:11:09.640
and it's your fault. And
in the real experiment,

01:11:09.640 --> 01:11:12.480
she then says-- we had
just moved in, it shows,

01:11:12.480 --> 01:11:16.090
which is true at the
beginning of the movie.

01:11:16.090 --> 01:11:18.360
She says, if this
is the real you,

01:11:18.360 --> 01:11:20.176
I don't want to continue
my relationship.

01:11:20.176 --> 01:11:21.050
We had just moved in.

01:11:21.050 --> 01:11:22.700
We were planning to get married.

01:11:22.700 --> 01:11:23.616
And so that's her own.

01:11:23.616 --> 01:11:25.665
She's willing to give up
a romantic relationship,

01:11:25.665 --> 01:11:29.420
a marital relationship for a
moral principle about kids she

01:11:29.420 --> 01:11:32.750
doesn't even though, but
she saw the suffering.

01:11:32.750 --> 01:11:35.660
So for me, that's really heroic.

01:11:35.660 --> 01:11:40.570
So a hero is somebody who comes
to the aid of others in need

01:11:40.570 --> 01:11:43.160
and/or defends a moral cause
aware that there's cost.

01:11:43.160 --> 01:11:44.882
So altruism is heroism light.

01:11:44.882 --> 01:11:46.090
You give money to the church.

01:11:46.090 --> 01:11:47.530
It doesn't cost you.

01:11:47.530 --> 01:11:50.110
So heroes are rare,
only because people

01:11:50.110 --> 01:11:52.700
in weighing the situation
say it's not worth it.

01:11:52.700 --> 01:11:55.080
So whistleblowers
are proactive heroes.

01:11:55.080 --> 01:11:56.949
You see fraud, you
see corruption.

01:11:56.949 --> 01:11:57.990
You have to collect data.

01:11:57.990 --> 01:11:59.850
Often, you have to get
people on your side.

01:11:59.850 --> 01:12:05.170
Most heroes are
really more impetuous.

01:12:05.170 --> 01:12:07.262
You react to the situation
like the famous hero

01:12:07.262 --> 01:12:08.470
in New York, the subway hero.

01:12:08.470 --> 01:12:09.890
A guy falls on the tracks.

01:12:09.890 --> 01:12:11.890
He jumps on the
railroad track, puts

01:12:11.890 --> 01:12:15.100
the guy between the tracks
as the train goes over them.

01:12:15.100 --> 01:12:17.370
For half an inch, he would've
been a dumb, dead hero.

01:12:17.370 --> 01:12:18.950
It would've cut his head off.

01:12:18.950 --> 01:12:24.430
So essentially, when
we finish this study--

01:12:24.430 --> 01:12:28.590
when I started writing "Lucifer
Effect," I realized that I know

01:12:28.590 --> 01:12:32.880
nothing about heroes, because
I started the last chapters,

01:12:32.880 --> 01:12:35.130
how do you resist
these powerful forces?

01:12:35.130 --> 01:12:37.310
In all the research,
in all the studies

01:12:37.310 --> 01:12:40.680
of evil in the real world in the
Holocaust, in Bosnia, Rwanda,

01:12:40.680 --> 01:12:43.920
there's always a small
percentage, 5%, 10%,

01:12:43.920 --> 01:12:47.130
never more than 30% of
people who do what-- resist.

01:12:47.130 --> 01:12:47.950
I won't go along.

01:12:47.950 --> 01:12:48.783
They don't go along.

01:12:48.783 --> 01:12:51.180
In some cases, they not
only don't go along.

01:12:51.180 --> 01:12:53.360
They challenge the evil.

01:12:53.360 --> 01:12:55.810
And I said, you know, I don't
know anything about heroes.

01:12:55.810 --> 01:12:57.393
I never thought about
it, and I should

01:12:57.393 --> 01:12:59.700
have given this woman
who challenged me,

01:12:59.700 --> 01:13:01.900
and we've been
married for 44 years.

01:13:01.900 --> 01:13:05.830
So I began to do research,
library research on heroes.

01:13:05.830 --> 01:13:07.630
Turns out the word
hero and heroism

01:13:07.630 --> 01:13:10.550
does not exist in any
psychology textbook.

01:13:10.550 --> 01:13:13.780
It's not part of the
positive psychology movement,

01:13:13.780 --> 01:13:18.410
because compassion and
empathy are virtues.

01:13:18.410 --> 01:13:20.500
Heroism is a civic action.

01:13:20.500 --> 01:13:22.990
So essentially, I begin to
say, hey, wait a minute.

01:13:22.990 --> 01:13:24.720
What good is
compassion and action

01:13:24.720 --> 01:13:27.440
if it doesn't lead to
action, because action

01:13:27.440 --> 01:13:29.640
is what changes the world?

01:13:29.640 --> 01:13:33.130
So I started seven years
ago in San Francisco

01:13:33.130 --> 01:13:36.340
a nonprofit called the
Heroic Imagination Project.

01:13:36.340 --> 01:13:39.500
The simple goal is to teach
people, all people, especially

01:13:39.500 --> 01:13:43.360
young people, to learn how to
express the inner hero that you

01:13:43.360 --> 01:13:44.590
all have, especially as kids.

01:13:44.590 --> 01:13:46.120
We really had this inner hero.

01:13:46.120 --> 01:13:49.950
Not through superheroes,
which is dramatic,

01:13:49.950 --> 01:13:51.960
but the wrong direction,
because superheroes

01:13:51.960 --> 01:13:54.410
don't have the most
important thing in the world

01:13:54.410 --> 01:13:56.280
that every kid has is a brain.

01:13:56.280 --> 01:13:59.170
They are the creation of
somebody with a creative brain.

01:13:59.170 --> 01:14:01.540
So we say, you have
something they don't have,

01:14:01.540 --> 01:14:03.764
and with your brain you
could create anything.

01:14:03.764 --> 01:14:05.430
So essentially, we're
going to teach you

01:14:05.430 --> 01:14:07.810
how to be a wise and
effective hero, how

01:14:07.810 --> 01:14:11.360
to analyze social
situations, how

01:14:11.360 --> 01:14:13.630
to take wise and
effective action,

01:14:13.630 --> 01:14:16.760
but the point is we want to
inspire you to always take

01:14:16.760 --> 01:14:18.090
the right action.

01:14:18.090 --> 01:14:20.370
Stand up, speak out in
challenging situations

01:14:20.370 --> 01:14:22.991
starting in your family, in
your school, in your community.

01:14:22.991 --> 01:14:24.490
And then we have a
training program.

01:14:24.490 --> 01:14:28.130
We teach people how to do this,
and then the other thing we do

01:14:28.130 --> 01:14:32.290
is I started a
revolution in education.

01:14:32.290 --> 01:14:35.900
We have a number of lessons
about the bystander effect,

01:14:35.900 --> 01:14:39.220
about-- I know Carol Dweck was
here from Stanford last week.

01:14:39.220 --> 01:14:41.800
How do you transform
a fixed mindset,

01:14:41.800 --> 01:14:44.840
which is to say I'm good or
not good at this, to a growth

01:14:44.840 --> 01:14:45.480
mindset?

01:14:45.480 --> 01:14:48.370
I'm good at anything if I put
in enough practice and effort.

01:14:48.370 --> 01:14:50.580
How to reverse
prejudice, how to change

01:14:50.580 --> 01:14:53.510
groups that have negative
influence to positive,

01:14:53.510 --> 01:14:55.610
so we call this
understanding human nature,

01:14:55.610 --> 01:14:57.470
and we have six
of these programs.

01:14:57.470 --> 01:15:00.435
We hope to have four
more on conservation

01:15:00.435 --> 01:15:02.320
and sustainability.

01:15:02.320 --> 01:15:04.780
But what's revolutionary
is teachers don't teach.

01:15:04.780 --> 01:15:08.500
We give them a script,
and all the programs

01:15:08.500 --> 01:15:10.822
organize around powerful
videos, because kids

01:15:10.822 --> 01:15:11.780
live in a visual world.

01:15:11.780 --> 01:15:14.290
We show a video, and instead
of having a class discussion,

01:15:14.290 --> 01:15:16.926
the teacher has pairs,
pairs or triads.

01:15:16.926 --> 01:15:18.800
And we try to have a
boy and a girl together,

01:15:18.800 --> 01:15:20.300
because boys never
answer in class.

01:15:20.300 --> 01:15:21.360
Girls always do.

01:15:21.360 --> 01:15:23.980
And so essentially,
you show the video

01:15:23.980 --> 01:15:26.890
of a failure of a
bystander, and then you say,

01:15:26.890 --> 01:15:28.160
what were the people thinking?

01:15:28.160 --> 01:15:29.034
Why didn't they help?

01:15:29.034 --> 01:15:30.010
What would you do?

01:15:30.010 --> 01:15:31.370
What's the difference between
looking in at a situation

01:15:31.370 --> 01:15:32.420
and being in?

01:15:32.420 --> 01:15:34.410
Then we show them the
Kitty Genovese video,

01:15:34.410 --> 01:15:36.600
and we say, how does
anybody study this?

01:15:36.600 --> 01:15:39.770
Then we show them video
of social psychologists

01:15:39.770 --> 01:15:40.750
study this.

01:15:40.750 --> 01:15:43.440
And then we say,
when should you help?

01:15:43.440 --> 01:15:45.490
When should you not help?

01:15:45.490 --> 01:15:47.789
And then think of a
time when you helped.

01:15:47.789 --> 01:15:49.330
Think of a time when
you didn't help.

01:15:49.330 --> 01:15:52.310
And then we go through, so
each of the six programs

01:15:52.310 --> 01:15:53.870
has the same eight activities.

01:15:53.870 --> 01:15:57.320
So once the teacher learns to
do one, it's easy to transfer.

01:15:57.320 --> 01:16:01.210
And then the key is at the end,
you say, OK, spread the word.

01:16:01.210 --> 01:16:03.147
That's activity eight.

01:16:03.147 --> 01:16:03.980
What does that mean?

01:16:03.980 --> 01:16:05.860
What's the most interesting
thing you learned today?

01:16:05.860 --> 01:16:06.970
And the kid writes it.

01:16:06.970 --> 01:16:08.820
Now tell somebody.

01:16:08.820 --> 01:16:09.980
They write it down.

01:16:09.980 --> 01:16:12.870
Tell your mother, your cousin,
your bus driver, the grocery

01:16:12.870 --> 01:16:16.760
man, and then the next week
says, what did your mother say?

01:16:16.760 --> 01:16:18.225
My mother couldn't believe it.

01:16:18.225 --> 01:16:20.600
How could it be that when
there's a lot of people around,

01:16:20.600 --> 01:16:21.210
nobody helps?

01:16:21.210 --> 01:16:23.030
It's better to have just one.

01:16:23.030 --> 01:16:23.670
Now go back.

01:16:23.670 --> 01:16:26.270
Ask your mother if she
could tell one other person.

01:16:26.270 --> 01:16:30.450
So now this little lesson, which
we now have in remote areas

01:16:30.450 --> 01:16:32.470
in Hungary.

01:16:32.470 --> 01:16:35.130
Some mother is telling the
butcher about the bystander

01:16:35.130 --> 01:16:36.420
effect.

01:16:36.420 --> 01:16:40.690
So in that sense, it's really
a revolution in education.

01:16:40.690 --> 01:16:43.850
And the problem we have
is we started here.

01:16:43.850 --> 01:16:47.400
We cannot get our program in
any San Francisco high school,

01:16:47.400 --> 01:16:51.490
because the high schools,
they say, if it's not STEM,

01:16:51.490 --> 01:16:54.750
it's not preparing for the
exams, we can't work it in.

01:16:54.750 --> 01:16:58.010
So our program is all over
Hungary, it's all over Poland,

01:16:58.010 --> 01:17:01.540
it's in Corleone, the
Godfather town in Sicily,

01:17:01.540 --> 01:17:06.730
and so right now we're
trying to-- we just applied

01:17:06.730 --> 01:17:08.720
for a Google community
grant, because I

01:17:08.720 --> 01:17:10.480
have virtually no staff.

01:17:10.480 --> 01:17:12.440
But we have a hero
factory in my basement.

01:17:12.440 --> 01:17:14.760
We're creating these
little, little heroes.

01:17:14.760 --> 01:17:15.760
So we need a staff.

01:17:15.760 --> 01:17:20.460
We need sophisticated help
to move it to the next level.

01:17:20.460 --> 01:17:21.460
So we have the material.

01:17:21.460 --> 01:17:25.050
We have the desire
and the inspiration.

01:17:25.050 --> 01:17:26.050
MALE SPEAKER: Wonderful.

01:17:26.050 --> 01:17:26.840
Well, thank you both.

01:17:26.840 --> 01:17:27.680
